    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="593"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">General <persName type="from">Marshall</persName> to the
                        Commander of the Seventh Fleet</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cooke</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-07">7 November
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1729.<note n="85" xml:id="d593fn85">Copy sent to the Naval Attaché (Kenny), for
                        transmittal to Admiral Cooke, by Col. J. Hart Caughey in his memorandum No.
                        565, November 7.</note> General Marshall forwarded on 5 November, a
                    memorandum (OSE 556<note n="86" xml:id="d593fn86">Not printed.</note>) to
                    General Chou, asking his immediate interest in securing the release of two
                    Marines captured in the vicinity of Hsin Ho. General Chou En-lai’s reply
                    received this date states: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I was informed that the two Marines referred to in your memo OSE 556 had
                            already been released. However I am sending another wire to ask for
                            confirmation. (Signed) Chou En-lai.”<note n="87" xml:id="d593fn87"
                                >Telegram No. 071355Z, November 8, by Major General Howard to
                                Admiral Cooke stated: “Two missing Marines released by Communists
                                reached Tientsin 1900H 7 November unharmed.”</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For General Marshall: <lb/>
                    <signed>J. <hi rend="smallcaps">Hart Caughey</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Colonel G. S. C.</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
